Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed with mental illness and now she is making art on the subject - "A person should have a right to his own body"
Dozens of patient stories hang from the roof of the Academy of Fine Arts’ Project room.
They all have Camille Auer's name on them.
The papers tell a multi-year story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
“I wanted to tell you about my person-specific treatment history so that the violence in the process would become visible,” Auer says.
By the process, he refers to the process of gender correction.
It is often a period of years of research involving meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process will start with a referral to diagnose studies of "gender identity disorder" carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
In the case of Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, he had used the estrogen he had ordered over the internet and was already very advanced in his own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must undergo a correction process in order to be able to correct gender legally.
The Trans Act, or Act on the Confirmation of the Gender of Transsec Sual (563/2002), obliges transgender people to be forced to sterilize so that the correct gender can be obtained, for example, in the Population Register Centre and in the passport.
At present, every person who corrects their gender is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and proof of reproductive incapacity.
People have the right to decide their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the Trans Act has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has made eight comments on the law and the European Court of Justice has a precedent that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect the right to self-determination.
Finland’s previous government prepared an amendment to the Act under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
There was an election and the Finns Party came to the government.
Now the law change is stuck again.
These are domestic disputes that are not even related to this law.
“The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government over the amendment of the law,” says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty Finland.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of packaging and instructions for use of medicines used by Auer.
In the patient record installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by a transpolitan psychologist at Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on these wrote a story that would define Auer's right to treatment and assistance.
The sense of the reality under study appears to be exposed to wavering.
The subject’s perception of themselves appears to be fragmented at the borderline level, and the unstable features related to personality are highlighted.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with mental illness," Auer says.
An even greater shock was when Auer was not given sex-repair treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his identity.
On 11 February 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the television in the waiting lobby of the transpoly.
Later, an artwork called Monument for the Excluded emerged from that television, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
“It’s crazy that any person who is defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but a diagnosis is needed to remove their breasts,” Auer says.
Your body is not your own if you feel that you are anything other than the number of genders you are born with.
Unfortunately, Auer’s experience is not the only one of its kind.
The gender correction process is more difficult for many for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people who need to justify their own existence and right to their own sexual experience.
"It's crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment, arguing that their resources aren't enough," Auer says.
Many people who have applied for the process have mental symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible experiences of bullying.
Based on this, the medical professional may prescribe that treatment cannot be initiated.
"Preventing treatment and getting help can plunge a person into an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer’s personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
Auer wrote: “I’ve had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that’s something that people usually find difficult to digest.”
The depression has been treated with medication and when Auer started using hormones, it made me feel better.
He had finally been able to write down the feelings that had existed in childhood and in his teens.
The reason why the wide jaw didn’t seem to fit into your body and why your chest muscles had to be round instead of flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
“You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using voice and moving,” he says.
Today, Auer feels like she is already being seen, she exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, the random comments of loved ones could hurt a lot.
What hurts the most is when people close to you are mis-sexed.
"They should know and they know who I am, but they won't agree or be able to internalize it," he continues.
However, not all transgender people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a lengthy research process, there can be no official confirmation of one’s own sex.
“There is no medical basis for these studies,” Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination in relation to the legal gender.
The adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code, stating in it that he/she feels that he/she is of the other sex.
After a six-month period of reflection, the applicant will confirm his/her application in writing and the Ministry will assign the applicant a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland, and the Auer exhibition also crystallizes this demand.
It has not been a therapeutic experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a collection of political and artistic works.
I want to believe that art still holds weight and that it can bring about political change at a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
