Civil Rights Organization Issues Travel Warning to Missouri
The African-American Civil Rights National Association (NAACP) has issued a travel warning for Missouri due to discriminatory state practices and racist attacks there.
"NAACP's travel bulletin for Missouri comes into effect on August 28, 2017, and calls on African-American tourists, visitors, and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when travelling in a state that has recently experienced numerous questionable racial events," the organization said in a statement.
A law that recently came into force in Missouri makes it more difficult to bring cases of discrimination to justice. In addition, enforcement of state laws is disproportionately directed against minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issuing of a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They will be stopped on the basis of skin color and beaten or killed," NAACP Missouri president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases before in such a short time."
The Missouri Travel Bulletin is the organization's first warning regarding the state of the United States.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year, driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and was arrested by Missouri police even though he was not charged with the crime.
According to a report by the Missouri Attorney General, police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white driver.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be alert and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what may happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare, for example, by taking money with them to bail out or by telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, there were 100 hate crimes recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth highest number of states in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law that makes it harder to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The ACLU, a civil rights organization that supports constitutionally guaranteed rights, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws obliging police to arrest people for immigration violations, which, according to the organization, increases racial profiling.
In general, travel warnings are issued by the State Department and concern other states, but have recently been published by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
