Even if the Russian reaction is only offset by political rhetorical escalations and excesses, the tightening of relations between the United States and Russia is a fact after a brief honeymoon after Trump’s election.
In the United States, the passage of sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea was not simple.
Although Congress passed the bill with considerable unanimity, the president said it was much more difficult to pass the bill.
Trump recently criticized the bill he signed as “significantly flawed.”
The reason for President Trump’s unease must have been Russia in particular, even though the adoption of a law that restricts his own powers must have been repugnant.
As is well known, the US is under investigation for possible Russian interference in the presidential election as well as for the Trump campaign’s links with Russia.
The tightening of relations between the United States and Russia is a fact after a brief honeymoon.
As the White House staff has changed rapidly and various scandalous twists have been revealed almost to be updated, it seems increasingly clear that foreign policy is not made in the United States under the leadership of the President but in spite of the President.
Such a situation is by no means desirable.
If the relationship with Russia is complex in the United States, the same applies to the European Union.
In addition to economic sanctions, the tense security situation in the Union's core region of the Baltic Sea is tightening relations.
The EU has prominently highlighted the situation in Ukraine in its relations with Russia and called for the implementation of the Minsk Agreement.
Although the Union has so far remained united, at least on the surface, in its policy towards Russia, the interests of the Member States are quite different.
For a member country like Finland that does a lot of trade with Russia, economic sanctions have been a real pain in the ass.
The effects of the recent US sanctions law are still unclear.
There have been fears in the EU that sanctions will make it more difficult for many European companies to operate.
In Finland, the effects may be felt, for example, in the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project and possibly in the Fennovoima nuclear power plant project.
Acidity in Europe has been caused by the exclusion from sanctions of liquid natural gas ing, which is important for the US economy, for example.
Trade sanctions are a means of showing disapproval in world politics.
However, economic sanctions must be well thought out and precise.
Otherwise, they can easily do more harm than good.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Trump's White House has a Statue of Liberty
Intervening in statues is the surest sign of a change of power.
Americans know this as well as anyone else: the Iraqis, together with American soldiers, knocked down Saddam Hussein's statue in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the chief ideologists in the Trump administration, was well aware of what he was doing in a heated debate with CNN channel Jim Acosta.
Miller did not actually criticize the statue itself.
Had he done so, he would have been attacked by huge hordes of cruise organizers and figures imitating the Statue of Liberty.
The object of his attack was the importance of the statue and especially the fact that in 1903 a poem by Emma Lazarus was added to the statue's pedestal — 17 years after the statue was completed.
“I don’t want to go into its history now, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the whole world.
The poem was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller wasn’t wrong, but it’s not just history, as he said.
The key words of Lazarus are: “Your tired, your poor, your huddled masses yearning to breathe free, / The wretched refuse of your Teeming shore.”
The poem is now more topical than ever.
Miller was by no means engaged in literary criticism. He made it clear that "the poorest of the poor" are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The controversy over the importance of the Statue of Liberty is part of a broader political and cultural controversy over the importance of the United States.
After his death, Lazarus' friends campaigned for the poem to be attached to the statue's pedestal, well aware that the act was strongly political.
The statue was intended to embody the connections between French and American republicanism with a classic symbol, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in his poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the exiled.
Linking the poem to the image was a brilliant feminist coup d'état and a devastating attack on American nationalism.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to change it back to the original.
Rush Limbaugh — a mouthpiece who can now be regarded as some kind of omen of Trump — claimed in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty does not present an invitation to anyone, but is an early pioneer of the neoconservatives, taking the torch of the United States into a world covered by darkness: "Lady Liberty steps forward.
He's taking the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch does not point the way to the United States."
Rarely, Limbaugh was partly right.
The meaning of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on the point of view.
Lazarus saw it as the poor and weary but hopeful immigrants from the ship's deck after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people seeking shelter and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty comforts by giving hope and welcoming.
That’s not what Miller and Trump want.
Their torch does not point the way, but kindles the flames of hatred, their only source of strength.
