Blocking Critics on Facebook: Don’t run for public office if you can’t stand criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but the newspapers soon began to criticize him for all possible domestic politics, from his political principles.
The criticism must have been annoying.
But he did not silence his critics.
"If the freedom of speech is removed, we may be led as dumb and silent as sheep to be slaughtered," Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to Governor Larry Hogan of Maryland, who should be learning from Washington.
Hogan's staff have removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked their authors.
Hogan was sued by the U.S. Civil Rights Association earlier this week.
His staff considers the challenge to be unfounded, and the attitude was also understated online.
“What does it matter? It’s just Facebook,” many commenters said.
But it matters,
Especially in the case of Hogan.
Hogan is an amazingly popular Republican governor of a Democratic-controlled state.
He has received the second best rating among the 50 governors.
Hogan's not very responsive to a hothead.
He has been a staunch leader of the state and firmly adhered to the principles.
He has also used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his constituents and posted a picture of a bald head in chemotherapy there.
Therefore, blocking users entering the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax funds.
Hogan's spokesman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions in an interview with the Washington Post.
However, labeling commenters as trolls, spammers, or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to the leaders they elected, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They said that their comments were respectful, considerate and relevant.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his comment; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani from Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile but asked a question about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in comments to the Washington Post news.
"I also cannot accept that when more people comment on the same issue, they are immediately regarded as an organized group in some way and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens."
The governor's staff called the comments "focused attack," and someone else might call them "promoting things that are considered important."
In the age of Facebook, communication is easy to control by blocking a reviewer or removing a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence protesters.
It’s the same thing, now only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision was made last week in Virginia.
According to Judge James C. Cacheris of the Alexandria District Court, the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment to the United States Constitution by blocking a voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Rights League went to discuss the use of Twitter and Facebook with Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin.
This shouldn't be hard.
At the time of Washington, low-cost postage had a similar effect to what the internet does today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and Washington was hammered by anonymous writers.
At the time, there were trolls.
The pseudonyms Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters to newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticizing Jay's agreement, the US-British Cooperation, Trade and Shipping Agreement, as shown by documents collected by the Papers of George Washington network project.
However, he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of debate are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
The summer feeding of birds should be stopped immediately.
Samples have come from about a half a dozen places, plus online adverts from a couple of, three.
Most of them have come from Southern and Southwest Finland, but then from Haapavesi and Seinäjoki, says Senior Scientist Marja Isomursu from Evira.
Green finches have died of a parasitic disease called trichomonosis.
It is caused by a protozoan called Trichomonas gallinae.
It has previously been known to strike pigeons, and especially pigeons.
In the 21st century, however, the disease also began to be detected in finch birds.
In 2009 it went really well.
At that time, trichomonosis caused a major collapse in the Finnish green finch population, after which the species’ populations have been on the path to recovery.
There have now been sick green finches, but at least not yet on a large scale, says Juha Honkala, Museum Master of Natural History at the University of Helsinki (Luomus).
It is feared that the previous epidemic of green finches will recur again if something is not done.
What needs to be done now is a very simple thing that everyone can do: stop summer feeding birds immediately.
More on the subject later.
