Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Golden Land
Bardina Degei does not use stoves in cooking.
He rarely uses pots.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the troubled Papua province of Indonesia. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato — locally "nota" — directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the burnt sweet potato is eaten voraciously with bare, unwashed hands.
Degei's home has no furniture. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually also takes care of his daily chores, such as laundry in cloudy water retrieved from a nearby swamp.
The toilet office is provided by a bucket in a roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of his four wives and has not been assigned fields to care for.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot, and the soldiers must also be taken into account.
“No one dares to walk in the village after five in the evening,” Degei says.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in the Papuan Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger to the Jakarta government, which holds tight control of the area and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, the eastern part of the island being part of Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and bleak. The journey starts with an hour and a half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a stomach-wrinking five-hour drive by rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The town of about 19,000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated roofs of which have been dyed yellowish brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago tribesmen of Papua worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We didn't have any clothes like this," Degei says. She means her colorful, hand-woven wrap headdress, her dark skirt and her bright-colored blouse.
"We used to only have leaves covered in our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also a gold country of Indonesia.
Paniai is about the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000. Just a hundred miles from Paniai is Grasberg, the world's largest and most lucrative gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, United States.
In 2015, the mine generated $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
For Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the repressive presence of a strong Indonesian army.
The New York Times revealed in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and military local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers being paid up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater sovereignty threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, the Indonesian military has killed more than 500,000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands since 1969.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, mass killings in the Papuan tribal highlands in the 1970s took on the proportions of genocide.
Last year, more than 3,900 people were arrested by Indonesian police in peaceful protests in the area.
A 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane entitled We Will Lose Everything contains accounts of the previous year's atrocities, such as executions without trial, torture — rape and electrocution are particularly popular — and relentless attacks toward peaceful demonstrations.
“It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are cases every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as the natural resources of Papua attract migrants from the rest of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million people in the province, 83% are Christians, but the demographic is changing as Indonesians from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi migrate to the region in hopes of better livelihoods.
Javan warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable blend in peanut sauce.
It is difficult for locals to compete.
“Migrators have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market at a lower price than the locals,” says 24-year-old Abeth You, who is from Paniai and moved to the provincial capital for work.
"Local women lost their customers".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo — nicknamed Jokowi — promised in his 2014 election campaign to address the injustices and human rights violations in Papua.
Papua is made up of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Paniai, on his way to Jakarta Presidential Palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Yokowi in 2014 and expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You says.
Paniai experienced some kind of wavebase just two months after Jokow's October inauguration.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by a fire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on motorcycles from the dark.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should wear headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the accounts of the victims and the Witnesses, drunken soldiers captured and assaulted the children, beating them with rifles.
That's how one of the soldiers shot at the children.
