Some of the protesters began stoning police and military buildings.
When the atmosphere became hot, the soldiers received an order in the internal radio system: "If the crowds resist more than three times, shoot them to death." The information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine, which has not been made public to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the resident leader of the Kego Koto area, suspected the situation would get out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
