The lack of freedom of the press means that the Indonesian government is only under pressure from its immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific states — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands — called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate Papua's "numerous and widespread violations", including the Paniai shooting scene.
These states have also traditionally supported the Papuan Liberation Movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir denied the allegations and told reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia is still a democracy with freedom of the press, so covering up evidence of human rights violations would be difficult".
The locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on 4 May 2017, locals broke the silence and expressed their desire for freedom, according to an anonymous source who attended the meeting.
Indonesia has a presidential election in 2019, but the people of Papua say they are unlikely to vote for Yokowi anymore.
"Jokowi means well, but there are people around him who are involved in the shooting scene in Paniai," said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokow to know the situation of the Panais: they live under the rule of a greedy and unpredictable army in want and poverty, virtually without access to health care and education.
According to Gobai, the Panais, like other Papuans, consider their votes given to Yokowi to be a "debt" that must be repaid.
