A day after 15 states sued Scott Pruitt, head of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), Pruitt withdrew his previous decision to delay the implementation of smog-causing emissions-reducing decisions made during the Obama administration.
According to Pruitt, the change shows that the agency under his leadership takes better account of the needs of environmental decision-makers in the states than previous administrations.
Pruitt made no mention of the action brought against his previous decision before the Federal Court of Appeals.
Lands should start to comply with the ground-level ozone requirements for 2015 as of 1 October.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the implementation of the decisions for a year ahead so that his agency would have more time to familiarize itself with the plan because the agency "does not want to interfere with local decision-making or hinder economic growth".
Pruitt was the state's attorney general in Oklahoma before being appointed by President Donald Trump as the head of the EPA.
Since his arrival in Washington, D.C., Pruitt has repeatedly tried to prevent or delay the implementation of decisions opposed by the chemical industry and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's sudden change of mind is the latest setback to Pruitt's plan to ease regulations.
Last month, the Federal Court of Appeals in Washington, D.C., ruled that the head of the EPA exceeded his authority in an attempt to delay the implementation of the Obama administration's decision on oil and gas companies, which required the companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement on Wednesday night, Pruitt claimed that his turnaround on ozone regulations only strengthens EPA's cooperation with the states in a complex process aimed at meeting new requirements on schedule.
"During previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and then expected activist groups and others to sue it for an agreement on schedules," Pruitt said. He sued the Environment Agency more than ten times in his previous post.
"We do not believe in legal regulation and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously the regulation on our activities and the powers it confers on us."
However, the EPA statement stated that Pruitt may continue to use "its powers to delay the implementation of decisions as well as other legal powers" to ensure that the provisions "are justified and based on the best available information".
Republicans are pushing for a broader change in ozone regulations in Congress.
