"The EPA's change of mind as a result of our lawsuits is a significant victory for the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans exposed to the direct effects of smog in their communities," Schneiderman said.
In addition to New York, the lawsuit involved California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is generated when, for example, emissions from cars, power plants, oil refineries and chemical plants react to sunlight in the atmosphere.
