Georgia Massacre: Activists re-enact racist lynching in hopes of justice
A Ford Mercury-branded car passes a crowd in the small town of Monroe in rural Georgia and continues its journey towards the small Moore's Ford Bridge.
There are four black passengers and a white driver in the car, four armed men blocking the road before the car reaches the bridge.
The leader of the gang, a middle-aged man dressed in a striped suit, takes a deep breath from his cigar and peers through the windshield.
The passengers are scared.
"Roger, n--u!" the man stutters.
"Get out of the car!"
The screams break the silence when a young black man is pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this shocking event is just a reenactment that aired on July 22, 2017.
However, the sighs of shock are genuine when the noose is tied to "Roger"'s neck.
Since 2005, human rights organizations have been returning to the Moore's Ford Bridge to stage the events of 1946, when the Ku Klux Klan lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey.
No one has been charged with murder.
"It's puzzling that no one has been arrested during these years — even though the murderers live among us and many need to know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helps with the rearrangement.
"It is a stain of shame in history, but above all it is a burden that weighs upon our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old civil rights activist and former congressman of Georgia.
For him, the re-enactment is a startling call to action, and it also reminds Monroe's residents that the injustice has never been corrected.
"We want those responsible to go to trial. We want things to be brought to an end at last, and we want to recover from the grief and make peace, but above all we want justice," Brooks said.
"We can't recover and make peace until we get justice."
The coroner covers the body of the victim who died in the massacre in Georgia on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI documents received by NBC news, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of lynching.
However, no one was charged with murder.
Although the perpetrators have been free for decades, activists say the motives for the lynching have been known to locals all along: politics and sex.
In 1946, the Supreme Court gave blacks in the state of Georgia the right to vote for the first time in a presidential election. The Supreme Court issued its decision in April, and the elections were held in the summer.
According to the FBI, around the time of the election, an incident occurred in which a black tenant Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, in a fight that apparently concerned Malcom's wife Dorothy.
According to Brooks, it was rumored that Hester had had an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was pregnant with her child.
According to FBI records, on July 25, 1946, powerful white landowner Loy Harrison paid Malcom's $600 bail, for which he was released from prison.
On the way home, Malcom and Dorothy were accompanied by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
The crowd stopped their car before the Moore's Ford Bridge.
"It turns out that Harrison ordered and organized the murders," the FBI's report states.
"It is also obvious that there was a conspiracy between state and local authorities, who were involved in the murders and destroyed the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
"It was a voter murder," he says.
"They were murdered because they wanted to send a message to black people that the same thing would happen to them if they were going to vote."
Cassandra Greene has been directing the re-enactment of the Georgia massacre for nearly a decade.
It is extremely realistic and captivating, and it is a description of a shocking racism that many would like to believe has already disappeared from the present-day United States.
It’s hard to watch, but it’s even harder not to see what Greene says is meant to be.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because we'd have to face our own dark sides," the director says.
“But I can’t create a relationship with you if you can’t hear me or don’t want to hear what I’ve been through.”
The rehearsals for this year’s performance began in June. On the first day, about 30 actors — about a dozen blacks and twenty whites — gathered to listen to Greene’s routine summary of the performance.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's assistant director.
He has played a local leader of the Ku Klux Klan for years in the reenactment, but the role is always as difficult and repulsive.
“I feel dirty because I’m not myself,” Marbaugh said.
“It is important, however, that this aspect of history be brought up so that it never happens again.”
On the other side of the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, or Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, practice their lines.
The show begins with a scene in which Malcom screams and pushes Hester. He is furious that Hester has had an affair with Dorothy.
"Didn't you hear me? I said get out of my land, n--u!"
Rascona, or Hester, responds.
Then there's the punch.
And then everyone (at least all black actors) burst into laughter.
Greene laughs the hardest.
"What?" Rascona asks.
He's confused.
“Did I accidentally hit too hard?” he asks.
“No,” Greene said.
"I just don't think white people used the word n--u at the time."
“Yes,” another black actor said.
"It's slang. You'll have to use the longer version."
The subject of the performance is unpleasant, but the room is occupied by the spirit of friends.
Everyone wants to succeed, not just for the performance, but for the memory of those who have been killed.
The scene starts all over again.
Now Rascona's words are blazing.
No one's laughing.
The re-enactment ends quickly and violently.
Screaming, gunshots, and silence.
A woman dressed in a black funeral dress stands by the bodies and sings Billie Holiday's Strange Fruit song.
His voice breaks for every second word.
A few hundred feet away, about fifty spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
Almost half of the population is black and half white.
Among them is a couple who have come to see a show from Ithaca, New York, but most are local.
They have visited the graves of the victims under Brooks' guidance in the oppressive humidity of Georgia.
The murders have become a reality, and the atmosphere at the scene is heavy.
After the singing performance, Greene invites the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children squat to look at fake blood and motionless bodies and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," the little boy mutters as if to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Greene will thank the audience.
Actors who played lynchers take off their robes and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, a local Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Rascona hugs two actors and then bursts into tears after a hard performance.
"Don't worry," the woman in the show comforted.
"We know you're not him.
You did this for a good reason.”
Later, the audience and actors gather for a joint dinner.
A white couple from Altatta are busy discussing the show with a black couple they have just met.
Denise Duplinski finds it difficult to find words when she describes the feelings the performance evokes.
“It’s hard to listen to horrible words and watch the horrible things that are said and done by people who look like you — precisely because they look like you,” he says.
"My performance made me realize that lynchings still happen," he added. "They're just called arrests."
On the other side of the room, Brooks recalls the development of civil rights for listeners sitting at the same table.
He said he has already started planning for next year’s show.
“Resurrection is a powerful experience because it describes the horrors we experience, but it’s also an educational experience,” Brooks says.
"Its message is that this could happen again if we don't learn from it.
Those who do not know their history are doomed to repeat it."
