New results of Swedish asylum-seekers’ age tests published
The latest results of the medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been published. The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over the age of 18. However, not everyone finds the tests reliable.
The Swedish National Forensics Agency began testing earlier this year.
The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the actual age of applicants claiming to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has so far commissioned 6,880 tests, and the forensics office has now published the results of 2,481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Of those tested, 80%, or 2002 asylum seekers, were determined to be over 18 years of age, and in 25 cases, the Forensics Agency determined that the test was "possibly 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is "possibly under the age of 18".
The tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Bureau of Forensic Medicine says that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"The figures are fairly consistent. There are no major differences in previous months' statistics," he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years old, this does not necessarily mean that applicants have lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that there were "indicatives that the subject is 18 years of age or older" in 442 cases.
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes x-rays of the wisdom teeth and MRIs of the knee joints. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of humans. The assessment can be used to determine whether a person has reached puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I've had reason to think about it, and I think the method used is not the right one.
The determination of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he told Metro newspaper.
However, the forensic agency Göransson defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, one can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is low.
The risk is greatest in a situation where the test is about 18 years old, and the risk is about 10 per cent."
