Clubs are allowed to spend large amounts of money on acquiring players, but they need to be balanced with real sources of income so that the football-related business is not loss-making.
The fair play economic rules were drawn up on the initiative of Michel Platin, the French president of UEFA in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini felt that the pursuit of success through debt was cheating and led to serious problems if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of fair play economic rules shifted from clubs' debts to tracking their losses.
The change meant that the implementation of the business model first used by Roman Abramovich in Chelsea in 2003 became significantly more difficult. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums of money on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
The current three-year review period for fair play economy rules will run until 2018, during which time clubs will be allowed to make a maximum loss of €30 million.
Although Platini had to leave UEFA chairmanship in a scandalous way in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Ceferin, also wants to curb the reckless spending of clubs.
“The Fair Play rules are still in place and we will continue to apply them in the future,” Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for Fair Play Economics at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of its contract with a lump sum, it can amortise the amount in accounting for the entire duration of his new contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be booked as an annual expense of €44.4 million for the next five years.
Under fair play economic rules, the first sanctions were issued in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Manchester City, funded by Abu Dhabi.
PSG was fined €60 million, which was later reduced to €20 million and the club was ordered to limit its Champions League group to 21 players for the 2014-2015 season instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA monitors clubs that may try to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
For example, if a Qatari company supports PSG but the value of the aid is considered to be above the normal market level, UEFA does not count the aid as actual income.
This was the case when UEFA decided in 2014 that the Qatar Tourism Authority's support for PSG was overstated.
