Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged, as economic growth has been unyielding and the easing of inflation has put an end to speculation about interest rate increases.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue at a slow pace, shifting interest rates due to increasing pressure on families' income levels.
The decision-makers of the Central Bank's Monetary Policy Commission decided by a vote of six to ten to keep interest rates at 0.25%.
In its quarterly inflation review, the bank lowered its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and its forecast for 2018 to 1.6%. It also warned that household income levels will be under further pressure as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate by close to 3% in the autumn.
However, according to the bank, interest rate increases will be needed in the coming years to contain the inflation boosted by Brexit, and the bank announced that the cost of loans could have to increase more than expected in the financial markets.
In addition, members of the commission decided to cancel part of the massive economic package, which began to be implemented a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The Bank will close the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide preferential financing to banks in excess of £15 million, or a total of £115 million, through the programme.
The minutes of the Bank’s interest rate decision state: “According to the forecast of the Monetary Policy Commission, the slow development of GDP will continue in the coming years, as the decline in households’ real income reduces consumption.”
With regard to interest rates, the Bank reiterated that a "some tightening of monetary policy" of the market expectations "slightly wider" is needed to contain inflation.
The market currently forecasts the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that any increases would be "gradual" and "limited".
In May, the bank forecasted a growth rate of 1.9 per cent for this year and a growth rate of 1.7 per cent for next year.
Now it kept its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8 per cent.
The pound depreciated against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
Compared to the dollar, the pound depreciated by 0.5 per cent to 1.31 per cent and weakened by 0.4 per cent to 1.11.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged was made after weaker-than-expected growth figures dampened increased expectations of interest rate increases, with GDP growing by 0.3 per cent in the second quarter and 0.2 per cent in the first quarter.
The bank expects growth to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation review gave little hope to households suffering from rising inflation and low wage increases, and the bank says the situation will deteriorate even further before it gets better.
The bank added that monetary policy "can't stop" the decline in revenue in the coming years, however, it expects wage developments to recover "significantly" at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by the strong increase in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound sterling, which will offset part of the impact of the decline in private consumption.
The decision was taken one year after interest rates were lowered to 0.25% after a shock result in the EU referendum that plunged the pound sterling into decline.
The Bank estimates that the overall impact of the decision is likely to be reflected in prices and the economy only after four years.
Before the central bank’s latest decision, interest rate increases had been called for more and more loudly, as inflation put pressure on households, and three decision-makers in July called for a 0.5% interest rate increase.
Inflation eased to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, but according to the bank, it was expected and inflation will pick up again in the coming months.
According to the bank, the excess of its 2% target was due to a "totally" weak pound.
"Given the recent decline in swap rates, competition in the mortgage market seems to be getting even tighter as lenders are feverishly seeking customers and looking to end the year strongly," said Andrew Montlake, director of Coreco Mortgage Brokers.
"The market looks particularly good for those whose current loan agreement is coming to an end. Renewal agreements are increasingly popular, their interest rates are low and there are also cost-free options available."
NHS imposes 10,000 anti-HIV drugs
As of September, patients may be prescribed a "revolutionary" HIV inhibitor. The Supreme Court closed a dispute over the funding of the drug in the English Public Health System (NHS).
The NHS reported that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PreEP) is prescribed to approximately 10,000 people during the first three-year trial. Pre-conferencing medication has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by about 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld last year's ruling by the Supreme Court, which states that the NHS will be able to pay for the PrEP drug, although claiming that it should be funded by local authorities.
Simon Stevens, head of the NHS in England, called the decision announced on Thursday a "significant new intervention", and the National AIDS Organization described it as "a crucially important moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to accept registrations for the trial, which will expand to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full scope in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is an anti-HIV medicine that reduces the risk of infection before sexual intercourse.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in high-risk groups.
A medicine taken before sexual intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during intercourse to prevent HIV infection.
It can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The treatment target group includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving effective treatment.
The clinics select eligible candidates from men, women and transgender and those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and enrolled in general medical care can also apply for an experiment at their local sexual health clinic.
The program costs £10 million, and the NHS of England signed a procurement agreement this week for the medicines following an international tender.
The purpose of the experiment is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence of its targeting, uptake and implementation.
“This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the existing diverse and increasingly effective means of preventing HIV,” says Stevens.
“It’s yet another remarkable achievement in over 30 years of struggle to solve one of humanity’s greatest health challenges.”
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," said Deborah Gold, head of the National AIDS Agency.
“If PrEP is targeted correctly for those who need it and those at risk, it could have a life-changing impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, those in the high-risk group will receive, through an experiment funded by the NHS, a drug that they can decide on their own use without the need to negotiate with a partner. It has an empowering effect that will improve the lives of very many people.
This was welcome news.”
"The most important thing now is to make sure that the experiment is launched quickly across the country and that no one in the risk group is excluded from it," said Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP drug used in the experiment has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people at risk from HIV infection."
"The start of the PrEP experiment is a welcome event that was unnecessarily prolonged by several months due to the government's slowdown," said Sharon Hodgson, the shadow government's health minister.
"We have evidence that the drug can have a life-changing effect on the work we do to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The experiment will help us to better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the experiment is launched as soon as possible across the country, so that we can protect those exposed to HIV and get one step closer to halting the spread of HIV in society."
