When Ferrell was driving towards Ferguson with their daughter in a flower dress and a crown that matches it, they had another conversation about "what it's like to be black and under what conditions". They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
"Remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and it's not right."
"I couldn't help taking my daughter with me," Ferrell said later.
"Today's events are... the culmination of events in the past.
My daughter has a right to know that and to grow into it.
He must have the capacity for activism and organization, but he must also know the different layers and circumstances of the experience of living as a black person, and he must know what we need to do to free ourselves, to liberate ourselves.
Fortunately, while I have been able to protect her from flagrant racism, she is still the same as other black girls.
I feel like I would hurt him if I were to protect him from reality."
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, opposite the police station, which became a camp for activists as they waited for information about the case to be heard and eventually learned that no charges would be filed against the police.
From there Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," she says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was president of the Association of Minority Nurse Students. At the time, she focused on food law and health inequalities in black communities.
“I had no experience of organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the documentary's assistant director, at an evening demonstration.
