Do you really want to tell me what's going on, or do you want a story that you can take advantage of?"
Behind the suspicion were the countless times that people had appeared in the local community, usually whites, who wanted only to benefit from its hardships and perseverance.
"We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson had no common voice," Folayan said in a recent interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted assistant director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism among prisoners sentenced to death.
Davis' involvement led Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals. The film crew followed the events in the years following Brown's shooting.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, but we do," Davis says.
"For me, the most important thing was how the local people are portrayed in the film, because I'm portrayed in the same way."
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences because it was wanted to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader but about a community".
That's why the documentary sees surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs when he tells me what it was like to see the movie for the first time.
"But I realized that this work and the humane portrayal of blacks require a certain vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell's story reprises and re-establishes the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after police shot a black teenage boy, Trayvon Martin, in 2012.
"The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going," Ferrell says. "It's because we have to fight constantly on many fronts.
Black queer women have had to endure everything."
Folayan agrees, "The movement is indeed maintained by black women, among whom there are a lot of queer women."
However, he emphasizes that Ferrell was not selected for the documentary "self-purposed" due to his queer identity.
"He got the energy moving," Folayan says.
"It's no coincidence, however, that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
