The Origin of a Comic Book: The Story of a Castle
The small Castle of Scotney in County Kent is now known from Squeeze's music video as well as Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
However, it has 700 years of turbulent history behind it. Now, in a charming location in the river valley of Bewl, this castle is the subject of a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer fond of old documents.
“I’m delighted to be able to study a text written by someone who died over 300 years ago,” Rhodes says yearningly.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold a letter in my hand."
Rhodes' book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families living in Scotland from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from the National Library of Britain. The project was emotional.
"I was moved to tears when I noticed the thumbprint in the letter, written by a double agent who worked for Jacobites in the 18th century," Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprints!
And the letters smell like smoke, because fire was used as lighting at the time.
Three centuries later, the scent makes the reader feel that he or she is on the spot.
I love the archives!”
The writer, who was attracted to old documents, was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust and the National Arts Council of England, which seemed too good to be true.
He spent the days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures and rarities, such as hyena heads hung on walls and bottles in the moat for centuries.
He toured the ruins and estates of the old castle and talked with rangers, gardeners, and sometimes also artists illustrating the book.
In the evening, he “takes whiskey and begins to write.”
The closer history of Scotney is rather unknown, as the castle was completely transferred to the National Trust only after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the foundation’s staff were just starting to go through the archive. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking everything extra to the attic.
There were diaries in the archives, letters from the days of the English Empire, and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "Here, however, families fought even for one birch.
I thought we should let it go.”
Some of the stories in the book go from castle to English history, such as The Labourer, about a man who joins the English peasant rebellion shortly after the castle's completion in 1381.
"The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex book mentions that there was a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
"The peasant revolt in England began in the same area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion can begin with a riot.
Maybe these events are related?”
The other stories in the book are closely linked to the history of the castle — such as The Priest, a story of a priest that was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler tells the story of Arthur Darrell, a smuggler from the 18th century. He is said to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (it was discovered years later when his grave was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. "The men in the family seem to have been quite the scoundrels. They kept getting into debt and buying things they couldn't afford.
The men of the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women, and I see them as handsome guys who could court heiresses."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Elämenmäki, a sanatorium in the early 20th century, of which only a eutrophication plot remains.
Scotney Castle has a special place in his heart.
“It was sad to leave,” he said.
“I didn’t want to go back to this damn thing.”
