Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares in the digestive system.
However, a recent study argues the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may help relieve irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the United Kingdom. It causes abdominal cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Irritable bowel syndrome sufferers are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen bowel tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, director of the study, immune cells guard the intestine and ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not enter the body.
The cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen resilience. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, the result can be irritable bowel syndrome.
The studies found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice with a specific bacterium in their intestines.
This bacterium needs tryptophan to make immune cells appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
“We found a link between the development of Lactobacillus reuteri and cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal gut microbiome,” says Professor Colonna.
"The more tryptophan in the mice' diet, the more immune cells they had."
If the same thing works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a high-tryptophan diet can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
In a study of immune cells that strengthen tolerance, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from another group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiomes of mice, i.e. the normal community of bacteria, fungi, and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the mice were tested for intestinal DNA, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells, but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that had grown up in a sterile environment and had no intestinal microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system, growing Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in the liquid and transferring small amounts of fluids — without bacteria — to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells developed into tolerance-boosting cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice’ food, the number of cells that strengthened tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When tryptophan was halved, the number of cells dropped by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," Cervantes-Barragan says.
"High tryptophan levels combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their prevalence".
